      <h2>Gas hot-water generator and LA natural-gas economics</h2>
      <p>
        Higher-tier Fagor E-VO and EVO Concept+ HRS configurations offer an integrated natural-gas hot-water
        generator — a ventless on-demand combustion module that produces 180°F final-rinse water directly from
        natural gas, instead of relying on the building hot-water supply or an electric booster element. Fagor
        claims up to 60% energy savings versus comparable electric-booster architectures. The actual LA savings
        depend on your specific electric-versus-natural-gas utility rate structure.
      </p>
      <p>
        At LA's current commercial natural-gas rates from SoCalGas and the commercial electric rates from LADWP
        and Southern California Edison, the gas hot-water generator is usually economically viable at medium-to-high
        wash volumes — typically above 200 racks per day. At lower volumes, the payback period extends beyond
        typical equipment lifecycle and the electric-booster configuration is a better fit. If you're considering
        retrofit from electric-booster to gas-hot-water-generator, we can run the math on your specific utility-rate
        structure during a service call. This is the kind of technical+financial advisory that most general-appliance
        service companies don't offer; we do because it often saves operators meaningful money over the equipment
        lifecycle.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

